1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 ({The complications that
arise after} 5... Bh5 6. Nc3 e6 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 {usually favour White.}) 6.
Qxf3 e6 7. Bd3 ({White can also choose a more challenging setup:} 7. Nc3 Nbd7
8. Bd2 {followed by queenside castling.}) 7... Nbd7 8. O-O Bd6 9. Nc3 O-O {
White has a pair of bishops, but Black's position has no weaknesses.
Objectively, the position is very close to equal.} 10. Bd2 Re8 11. Qd1 {The
white queen can achieve nothing on f3, where it might be attacked by e6-e5-e4,
and it is transfered to either c2 or b3, according to circumstances.} dxc4 (
11... Bc7 12. Qc2 (12. Qb3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nb6 14. Be2 e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Rad1
Qe7 $11) 12... Rc8 13. Rad1 Qe7 14. Rfe1 e5 15. cxd5 e4 16. Bf1 cxd5 17. Qb3
Nb6 18. Nb5 Bb8 19. Rc1 Qe6 20. Bb4 {1/2-1/2 Cheparinov,I (2713)-Movsesian,S 
(2677)/Wijk aan Zee NED 2008/The Week in Chess 688}) 12. Bxc4 Qe7 $146 {Levon
improves on his own play. Black prepares the e6-e5 advance which was
impossible right away in view of Qd1-b3. The move 12...a6, previously played
by him, seems to me to be less useful.} (12... a6 13. Qc2 (13. a4 $6 {This
move weakens the b4-square.} c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Rfd1 Qe7 17. Rac1
Rc7 18. Be1 Rec8 19. Be2 h6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Ivanchuk,V (2740)-Aronian,L (2763)/
Sofia BUL 2008/The Week in Chess 706 (26)}) 13... c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Rfd1 Rc8
16. Be1 Qe7 17. Rac1 Rc7 18. Be2 Rec8 19. Qb1 h6 20. Bf3 g6 21. Ne2 Rb8 22. Nf4
$14 {1-0 Ivanchuk,V (2781)-Aronian,L (2737)/Sochi RUS 2008/The Week in Chess
717 (44)}) 13. Qc2 ({Black doesn't experience any difficulties after} 13. Qb3
Nb6 14. Be2 e5 {as well.}) 13... e5 14. Rae1 $6 {I don't like this move. I
think that White should develop his rooks to d1 and e1 respectively. The move
in the text could be justified only in the event that White manages to open
the f-file but, this can happen only with Black's assistance.} (14. Rfe1 Rad8
15. Rad1 Bb8 (15... Nb6 16. Bb3 e4 17. a4 Nbd5 {is equal but, White is not
worse here compared to the game.}) 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Nb6 18. Bb3 exd4 19.
Qxe7 Rxe7 20. exd4 {and White is very slightly better thanks to his great
light-squared bishop.}) 14... Rad8 (14... e4 $2 {would play into White's hands.
} 15. f3 exf3 16. Rxf3 $36) 15. Bb3 (15. f4 $6 {creates weaknesses only for
White.} exd4 16. exd4 Qf8 17. Bb3 Bc7 $1 18. Na4 (18. d5 Qc5+ 19. Kh2 Nxd5 20.
Nxd5 Qxc2 21. Bxc2 cxd5 $15) 18... b5 19. Nc5 Qd6 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) 15... Bb8
16. Ne2 (16. Ne4 exd4 17. Nxf6+ (17. Ng5 $2 {[%csl Rf7]} d3 $1 18. Qxd3 Ne5 19.
Qc3 h6 $19) 17... Qxf6 18. exd4 Qxd4 19. Bc3 Qd6 20. g3 {with sufficient
compensation for the pawn at best.}) 16... Qd6 17. g3 Nb6 18. Qf5 $6 {This
queen move is suspicious.} (18. dxe5 $2 Qxd2 19. Qxd2 Rxd2 20. exf6 gxf6 $17 {
[%csl Rb2]}) (18. a3 e4 (18... c5 $6 19. dxc5 Qxd2 20. cxb6 Qxc2 21. Bxc2 Rd2
22. Ba4 Rf8 23. bxa7 Bxa7 24. Nc3 Rxb2 25. Rb1 $14) 19. Rc1 Nbd5 {is obviously
fine for Black, but his kingside offensive is far from being dangerous. For
instance, an attempt at transfering the queen to f3 does not work:} 20. Nc3 Qd7
21. Kg2 Qf5 $6 22. f4) 18... Nbd5 19. Qf3 e4 20. Qg2 h5 21. Nf4 g6 {Protecting
the Ph5 and preparing the transfer of the Nf6 to better pastures.} (21... h4 $6
22. Nxd5 cxd5 23. gxh4 Re6 24. Bd1 Nh7 25. h5 Ng5 26. f4 exf3 27. Bxf3 {and it
won't be easy for Black to justify the pawn sacrifice.}) 22. Rc1 Nh7 23. Ba5 {
Trying to provoke a concession on the queenside.} (23. Nxd5 cxd5 24. h4 $11 {
would have been safer.}) 23... b6 24. Bd2 Ng5 25. Bd1 h4 26. gxh4 {This looks
nervous but, actually, this move is not bad, the decisive mistake came a bit
later...} (26. Nxd5 Qxd5 27. gxh4 Nf3+ 28. Bxf3 exf3 29. Qg4 Qd6 30. Qg3 Qf6
31. Qg4 Kg7 $17 {[%cal Ge8h8]}) ({It was possible to play a "waiting" move} 26.
Kh1 $5 {even though White's position looks somewhat cramped.}) 26... Nxf4 27.
exf4 Ne6 28. h5 $2 {Wrong push.} (28. f5 {could keep the tension in the game.
Here is how the game could continue:} Nxd4 29. fxg6 fxg6 (29... f5 $2 30. Bg5
Rd7 31. h5 f4 32. h4 f3 33. Qh3 $16) 30. Rc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3g3]} Kh7 (30... Nb5
31. Rc1 Qxd2 32. Qxg6+ Kh8 33. Qf6+ Kh7 34. Qf7+ Kh6 35. Qf6+ {with a
perpetual check.}) 31. Bg5 Rd7 32. h5 gxh5 33. Bxh5 Rg8 34. h4 $13) 28... Nxd4
29. Be3 c5 30. Bxd4 ({Now even the exchange of queens would not make White's
life much easier.} 30. hxg6 Qxg6 31. Qxg6+ fxg6 $17 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Ge8f8]})
30... cxd4 31. Ba4 Re7 32. Rc6 (32. f5 {Now it's too late.} g5 $1 33. h4 (33.
Qxg5+ Kh7 $19 {[%cal Gd8g8,Gd6h2]}) 33... g4 34. Rc6 Qf4 35. Bd1 Kh8 $1 {is
lost for White. His doubled pawns on the kingside look terrible compared to
Black's proud central pawns.}) 32... Qxf4 33. hxg6 f5 {Black's monarch feels
quite safe behind the white pawn.} 34. Rfc1 d3 35. Rc8 {The exchange of rooks
makes Black's task easier but, White's position is lost anyway.} Kg7 $1 36.
R1c4 Rxc8 37. Rxc8 Rc7 38. Rxc7+ Bxc7 39. Bd7 a6 40. h4 b5 41. Qh3 d2 0-1

